<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Thailand-LaosBorder     02-16 0169</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Thailand-Laos Border,0174</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Talks Over Border Conflict Said To Show Promise</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thai and Laotian army chiefs today
discussed how to end a bloody border conflict, and a Thai spokesman
said there was a good chance the talks would lead to full-scale
talks between the countries.
   The nearly six hours negotiations were the first between top
officials since the fighting flared in November.
   Gen. Sisavat Keobounphan, chief of general staff of the Lao
People's Army, and Gen. Chaovalit Yongchaiyuth, commander-in-chief
of the Royal Thai Army, each led four-man military teams in the
talks in Bangkok.
   The Thai spokesman, Air Vice Marshal Sommot Sundaravej, said
they discussed a cease-fire and how far troops of both sides should
withdraw from the disputed hills where they have fought, incurring
hundreds of casualties.
   The border confrontation is the bloodiest since pro-West
Thailand and communist Laos clashed over three villages in 1984.
   Talks are to resume Wednesday, and both sides agreed not to
divulge details of the discussions until then.
</TEXT>
