<HEAD>Ship With Romanians, Bulgarian Stowaways Sails to Malta</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PIRAEUS, Greece (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A ship carrying 17 stowaways from Romania
and Bulgaria steamed out of port Tuesday for Malta, although the
group had requested political asylum in Greece, a port authority
spokesman said.
   The Maltese-flagged cargo ship Captain Yiannis set sail seven
hours after docking in Piraeus harbor, said the spokesman, who
requested anonymity.
   ``The stowaways asked for asylum as soon as the ship docked and
we started the paperwork but the ship had to leave and they went
with it,'' the spokesman said.
   He said the stowaways, identified only as 16 Romanians and one
Bulgarian, had boarded the vessel in Istanbul, Turkey.
   It was the third ship carrying refugees to dock in Piraeus in
the past four days.
   On Thursday, six Romanians stowaways on two cargo ships from
Istanbul asked for asylum. They were allowed to remain in Greece
while their requests were being processed.
