<HEAD>University of Michigan Creates Truck Statistics Center</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ANN ARBOR, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The University of Michigan has
established a Center for National Statistics to gather information
on truck safety and truck travel on U.S. highways, the university
said Tuesday.
   The center, which will be financed with public and private
money, will conduct surveys of truck accidents and travel, publish
statistics and conduct research on risk factors in accidents
involving large trucks, according to Linda Wilson, the university's
vice president for research.
   The center will use survey methods that allow accurate
compilation of fatal truck accidents and truck travel. The methods
were developed under an 8-year-old research program supported by
the Motor Vehicle Manufacturers Association and other federal and
trucking groups.
