<1ST_LINE>u i BC-SovietArms 2ndLd-Writethru a0661 02-16 0387</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Soviet Arms, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0661,0396</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>ADN: Soviets Have Begun Dismantling Intermediate Range Rockets</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: ADDS 7 grafs to UPDATE with more details of removal.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>BERLIN (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviet Union has begun dismantling
intermediate range nuclear rockets stationed in East Germany, the
state-run news agency ADN reported Tuesday night.
   According to the report, rockets stationed near Neubrandenburg,
north of Berlin, have been dismantled, crated and are ready for
transport back to the Soviet Union.
   Under a treaty signed in Washington in December by President
Reagan and Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev, the superpowers
agreed to eliminate the medium-range missiles.
   The U.S. Senate has yet to ratify the treaty.
   ADN said Soviet soldiers ``are making the last preparations to
return their SS-12 rockets'' to the Soviet Union.
   The rockets are shorter-range weapons included in the
intermediate range missile pact, which banned weapons with a range
from 300 to 3,000 miles.
   The news agency quoted a Soviet officer as saying that the
``troops are very proud that nuclear disarmament is beginning in
our unit.''
   ADN said a group of East German journalists toured the missile
base and were allowed to interview Soviet soldiers there.
   East German leader Erich Honecker in January indicated that
Soviet intermediate range rockets stationed in East Germany could
be removed ahead of schedule, but gave no specific timetable for
their withdrawal.
   The ADN report did not say how many rockets were ready for
transport back to the Soviet Union. It also did not say if other
missiles stationed in East Germany had been dismantled or how many
troops were scheduled to leave.
   The report, written by an ADN correspondent, described
preparations under way to ready the rockets for transport.
   Cranes were used to load the dismantled rockets into transport
containers, the report said.
   ``We were convinced that the last rockets were ready for
transport to the location where they will be destroyed,'' the ADN
correspondent said.
   The rockets are to be sent back to the Soviet Union by rail, the
report said.
   According to figures released after the superpower agreement was
signed, 22 rockets, 12 launchers, nine transport vehicles and seven
practice missiles were stationed at the site _ which holds the
largest numbers of SS-12s in East Germany.
   In all, there are 54 SS-12s in East Germany, the figures said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
