<1ST_LINE>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     02-16 0358</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0367</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cold Front Hits Mississippi Valley, Central Plains</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   A cold front swept across the central Plains and upper
Mississippi Valley on Tuesday, dropping up to 4 inches of snow and
drenching roads with freezing rain. Weather elsewhere was mostly
mild.
   Snow was scattered from southeastern Minnesota and northeastern
Iowa into central and eastern Wisconsin. Snow also fell across the
lower Great Lakes and upper Ohio Valley into northern New York
state and northern New England.
   In Wisconsin, 3 inches of snow fell at Neenah, Fond du Lac and
Sheboygan. Up to 4 inches were reported at Decorah and Cresco in
northeastern Iowa, and a few inches fell across southeast Minnesota.
   Scores of morning rush-hour traffic accidents were blamed on
freezing rain in northeastern Ohio.
   Elsewhere, snow showers developed across northern Colorado, but
only about 2 inches were expected.
   In Southern California, winds of 25 to 35 mph whipped the Owens
Valley and gusts of up to 40 to 50 mph were possible Wednesday.
   Heavier rainfall during the six hours ending at 1 p.m. EST
included 0.30 inch at Newport News, Va.
   Temperatures around the nation at 2 p.m. EST ranged from 12
degrees at Sault Ste. Marie, Mich., to 76 degrees at McAllen,
Texas, and Palm Springs, Calif. The early-morning low for the
nation was 14 degrees below zero at Gunnison, Colo.
   Wednesday's forecast called for scattered rain showers from
Arkansas and the lower Tennessee Valley into the lower Mississippi
Valley and eastern Texas, and across western and northern
Washington. Scattered snow showers were forecast in northwestern
Montana, upper Michigan and from northeastern Ohio through northern
New York state into northern Vermont.
   Highs in the 20s were forecast from the upper Mississippi Valley
across the northern Great Lakes and northern New England; in the
50s and 60s from Oregon across the western Great Basin, southern
Rockies, southern Plains, lower Mississippi and Tennessee valleys
into the southern Atlantic Coast region; in the 70s across southern
Texas, southern Florida and central and southern California into
the desert southwest; and in in the 30s or 40s across most of the
rest of the nation.
</TEXT>
