<HEAD>Steel Output Fell 0.4 Percent in Week</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Steel production fell to 1.867 million tons in
the week ended Feb. 13, a decrease of 0.4 percent from the previous
week's 1.875 million tons, the American Iron and Steel Institute
reported Tuesday.
   The industry's production amounted to 86.9 percent of capacity
during the week, compared with 87.3 percent in the previous week.
   Estimated figures for the year to date showed production at
11.696 million net tons, an increase of 38.3 percent from the 8.456
million net tons in the previous year.
   Production so far this year used 86.7 percent of capacity,
compared with 63.2 percent a year earlier.
   Net tonnage by district for the week ended Feb. 13: Northeast
Coast, 253,000; Pittsburgh, 197,000; Youngstown, 120,000; Lake
Erie, 149,000; Detroit, 152,000; Chicago, 521,000; Midwest,
181,000; Southern, 213,000; and Western, 81,000.
</TEXT>
